<p>Temperature scales require special handling because Celsius and Fahrenheit have offsets relative
to Kelvin. Measures handles these conversions correctly.</p>

<h3>Temperature Scales</h3>

<pre><code class="language-lean">open Measures.Units.Temperature

def freezing := 0.0 *: celsius
def boiling := 100.0 *: celsius
def body := 98.6 *: fahrenheit
def absolute := 0.0 *: kelvin</code></pre>

<h3>Conversions</h3>

<p>Temperature conversions account for both scale factor and offset:</p>

<pre><code class="language-lean">-- Celsius to Fahrenheit
#eval freezing.asUnit fahrenheit  -- 32.0
#eval boiling.asUnit fahrenheit   -- 212.0

-- Fahrenheit to Celsius
#eval body.asUnit celsius  -- 37.0

-- To/from Kelvin (absolute scale)
#eval freezing.asUnit kelvin  -- 273.15
#eval boiling.asUnit kelvin   -- 373.15</code></pre>

<h3>Why Offsets Matter</h3>

<p>Unlike length or mass where doubling a value doubles the measurement, temperature scales
have arbitrary zero points. Water freezes at 0°C = 32°F = 273.15K. Measures handles this
correctly:</p>

<pre><code class="language-lean">-- Direct conversion function
Unit.convert 100.0 celsius fahrenheit  -- 212.0
Unit.convert 32.0 fahrenheit celsius   -- 0.0
Unit.convert 0.0 kelvin celsius        -- -273.15</code></pre>

<h3>Temperature Differences</h3>

<p>When subtracting temperatures (to get a temperature difference), the offsets cancel out
and you get a pure temperature interval:</p>

<pre><code class="language-lean">-- Temperature change
def start := 20.0 *: celsius
def finish := 30.0 *: celsius
def change := finish - start  -- 10 K temperature difference

-- A 10°C change equals a 10 K change (scale factors match)
-- But a 10°C change is an 18°F change (different scale)</code></pre>

